542  if (!(co = PyCode_NewEmpty(fn_cstr, name_cstr, fline))) goto end;
543  if (!(replace = PyObject_GetAttrString((PyObject*)co, "replace"))) goto cleanup_code_too;
544  if (!(empty = PyTuple_New(0))) goto cleanup_code_too; // unfortunately __pyx_empty_tuple isn't available here
545  if (!(call_result = PyObject_Call(replace, empty, kwds))) goto cleanup_code_too;
546  Py_XDECREF((PyObject*)co);
547  co = (PyCodeObject*)call_result;
548  call_result = NULL;
549  if (0) {
550  cleanup_code_too:
551  Py_XDECREF((PyObject*)co);
552  co = NULL;
553  }
554  end:
555  Py_XDECREF(kwds);
556  Py_XDECREF(argcount);
557  Py_XDECREF(posonlyargcount);
558  Py_XDECREF(kwonlyargcount);
559  Py_XDECREF(nlocals);
560  Py_XDECREF(stacksize);
561  Py_XDECREF(replace);
562  Py_XDECREF(call_result);
563  Py_XDECREF(empty);
564  if (type) {
565  PyErr_Restore(type, value, traceback);
566  }
567  return co;
568  }
569 #else
570  #define __Pyx_PyCode_New(a, k, l, s, f, code, c, n, v, fv, cell, fn, name, fline, lnos)\
571  PyCode_New(a, k, l, s, f, code, c, n, v, fv, cell, fn, name, fline, lnos)
572 #endif

998 #if PY_MAJOR_VERSION < 3 && __PYX_DEFAULT_STRING_ENCODING_IS_ASCII
999 static int __Pyx_sys_getdefaultencoding_not_ascii;
1000 static int __Pyx_init_sys_getdefaultencoding_params(void) {
1001  PyObject* sys;
1002  PyObject* default_encoding = NULL;
1003  PyObject* ascii_chars_u = NULL;
1004  PyObject* ascii_chars_b = NULL;
1005  const char* default_encoding_c;
1006  sys = PyImport_ImportModule("sys");
1007  if (!sys) goto bad;
1008  default_encoding = PyObject_CallMethod(sys, (char*) "getdefaultencoding", NULL);
1009  Py_DECREF(sys);
1010  if (!default_encoding) goto bad;
1011  default_encoding_c = PyBytes_AsString(default_encoding);
1012  if (!default_encoding_c) goto bad;
1013  if (strcmp(default_encoding_c, "ascii") == 0) {
1014  __Pyx_sys_getdefaultencoding_not_ascii = 0;
1015  } else {
1016  char ascii_chars[128];
1017  int c;
1018  for (c = 0; c < 128; c++) {
1019  ascii_chars[c] = c;
1020  }
1021  __Pyx_sys_getdefaultencoding_not_ascii = 1;
1022  ascii_chars_u = PyUnicode_DecodeASCII(ascii_chars, 128, NULL);
1023  if (!ascii_chars_u) goto bad;
1024  ascii_chars_b = PyUnicode_AsEncodedString(ascii_chars_u, default_encoding_c, NULL);
1025  if (!ascii_chars_b || !PyBytes_Check(ascii_chars_b) || memcmp(ascii_chars, PyBytes_AS_STRING(ascii_chars_b), 128) != 0) {
1026  PyErr_Format(
1027  PyExc_ValueError,
1028  "This module compiled with c_string_encoding=ascii, but default encoding '%.200s' is not a superset of ascii.",
1029  default_encoding_c);
1030  goto bad;
1031  }
1032  Py_DECREF(ascii_chars_u);
1033  Py_DECREF(ascii_chars_b);
1034  }
1035  Py_DECREF(default_encoding);
1036  return 0;
1037 bad:
1038  Py_XDECREF(default_encoding);
1039  Py_XDECREF(ascii_chars_u);
1040  Py_XDECREF(ascii_chars_b);
1041  return -1;
1042 }
1043 #endif

1282  #define __Pyx_TraceDeclarations\
1283  static PyCodeObject *__pyx_frame_code = NULL;\
1284  CYTHON_FRAME_MODIFIER PyFrameObject *__pyx_frame = NULL;\
1285  int __Pyx_use_tracing = 0;

1288 #if PY_VERSION_HEX >= 0x030b00a2
1289  #define __Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, check_tracing, check_funcs)\
1290  (unlikely((tstate)->cframe->use_tracing) &&\
1291  (!(check_tracing) || !(tstate)->tracing) &&\
1292  (!(check_funcs) || (tstate)->c_profilefunc || (CYTHON_TRACE && (tstate)->c_tracefunc)))
1293  #define __Pyx_EnterTracing(tstate) PyThreadState_EnterTracing(tstate)
1294  #define __Pyx_LeaveTracing(tstate) PyThreadState_LeaveTracing(tstate)
1295 #elif PY_VERSION_HEX >= 0x030a00b1
1296  #define __Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, check_tracing, check_funcs)\
1297  (unlikely((tstate)->cframe->use_tracing) &&\
1298  (!(check_tracing) || !(tstate)->tracing) &&\
1299  (!(check_funcs) || (tstate)->c_profilefunc || (CYTHON_TRACE && (tstate)->c_tracefunc)))
1300  #define __Pyx_EnterTracing(tstate)\
1301  do { tstate->tracing++; tstate->cframe->use_tracing = 0; } while (0)
1302  #define __Pyx_LeaveTracing(tstate)\
1303  do {\
1304  tstate->tracing--;\
1305  tstate->cframe->use_tracing = ((CYTHON_TRACE && tstate->c_tracefunc != NULL)\
1306  || tstate->c_profilefunc != NULL);\

1308 #else
1309  #define __Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, check_tracing, check_funcs)\
1310  (unlikely((tstate)->use_tracing) &&\

1312  (!(check_funcs) || (tstate)->c_profilefunc || (CYTHON_TRACE && (tstate)->c_tracefunc)))
1313  #define __Pyx_EnterTracing(tstate)\

1315  #define __Pyx_LeaveTracing(tstate)\

1322  #ifdef WITH_THREAD
1323  #define __Pyx_TraceCall(funcname, srcfile, firstlineno, nogil, goto_error)\
1324  if (nogil) {\
1325  if (CYTHON_TRACE_NOGIL) {\
1326  PyThreadState *tstate;\
1327  PyGILState_STATE state = PyGILState_Ensure();\
1328  tstate = __Pyx_PyThreadState_Current;\
1329  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 1, 1)) {\
1330  __Pyx_use_tracing = __Pyx_TraceSetupAndCall(&__pyx_frame_code, &__pyx_frame, tstate, funcname, srcfile, firstlineno);\
1331  }\
1332  PyGILState_Release(state);\
1333  if (unlikely(__Pyx_use_tracing < 0)) goto_error;\
1334  }\
1335  } else {\
1336  PyThreadState* tstate = PyThreadState_GET();\
1337  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 1, 1)) {\
1338  __Pyx_use_tracing = __Pyx_TraceSetupAndCall(&__pyx_frame_code, &__pyx_frame, tstate, funcname, srcfile, firstlineno);\
1339  if (unlikely(__Pyx_use_tracing < 0)) goto_error;\
1340  }\
1341  }
1342  #else
1343  #define __Pyx_TraceCall(funcname, srcfile, firstlineno, nogil, goto_error)\
1344  { PyThreadState* tstate = PyThreadState_GET();\
1345  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 1, 1)) {\
1346  __Pyx_use_tracing = __Pyx_TraceSetupAndCall(&__pyx_frame_code, &__pyx_frame, tstate, funcname, srcfile, firstlineno);\
1347  if (unlikely(__Pyx_use_tracing < 0)) goto_error;\
1348  }\
1349  }
1350  #endif
1351  #define __Pyx_TraceException()\
1352  if (likely(!__Pyx_use_tracing)); else {\
1353  PyThreadState* tstate = __Pyx_PyThreadState_Current;\
1354  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 0, 1)) {\
1355  __Pyx_EnterTracing(tstate);\
1356  PyObject *exc_info = __Pyx_GetExceptionTuple(tstate);\
1357  if (exc_info) {\
1358  if (CYTHON_TRACE && tstate->c_tracefunc)\
1359  tstate->c_tracefunc(\
1360  tstate->c_traceobj, __pyx_frame, PyTrace_EXCEPTION, exc_info);\
1361  tstate->c_profilefunc(\
1362  tstate->c_profileobj, __pyx_frame, PyTrace_EXCEPTION, exc_info);\
1363  Py_DECREF(exc_info);\
1364  }\
1365  __Pyx_LeaveTracing(tstate);\
1366  }\
1367  }
1368  static void __Pyx_call_return_trace_func(PyThreadState *tstate, PyFrameObject *frame, PyObject *result) {
1369  PyObject *type, *value, *traceback;
1370  __Pyx_ErrFetchInState(tstate, &type, &value, &traceback);
1371  __Pyx_EnterTracing(tstate);
1372  if (CYTHON_TRACE && tstate->c_tracefunc)
1373  tstate->c_tracefunc(tstate->c_traceobj, frame, PyTrace_RETURN, result);
1374  if (tstate->c_profilefunc)
1375  tstate->c_profilefunc(tstate->c_profileobj, frame, PyTrace_RETURN, result);
1376  CYTHON_FRAME_DEL(frame);
1377  __Pyx_LeaveTracing(tstate);
1378  __Pyx_ErrRestoreInState(tstate, type, value, traceback);
1379  }
1380  #ifdef WITH_THREAD
1381  #define __Pyx_TraceReturn(result, nogil)\
1382  if (likely(!__Pyx_use_tracing)); else {\
1383  if (nogil) {\
1384  if (CYTHON_TRACE_NOGIL) {\
1385  PyThreadState *tstate;\
1386  PyGILState_STATE state = PyGILState_Ensure();\
1387  tstate = __Pyx_PyThreadState_Current;\
1388  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 0, 0)) {\
1389  __Pyx_call_return_trace_func(tstate, __pyx_frame, (PyObject*)result);\
1390  }\
1391  PyGILState_Release(state);\
1392  }\
1393  } else {\
1394  PyThreadState* tstate = __Pyx_PyThreadState_Current;\
1395  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 0, 0)) {\
1396  __Pyx_call_return_trace_func(tstate, __pyx_frame, (PyObject*)result);\
1397  }\
1398  }\
1399  }
1400  #else

1418 #if CYTHON_TRACE
1419  static int __Pyx_call_line_trace_func(PyThreadState *tstate, PyFrameObject *frame, int lineno) {
1420  int ret;
1421  PyObject *type, *value, *traceback;
1422  __Pyx_ErrFetchInState(tstate, &type, &value, &traceback);
1423  __Pyx_PyFrame_SetLineNumber(frame, lineno);
1424  __Pyx_EnterTracing(tstate);
1425  ret = tstate->c_tracefunc(tstate->c_traceobj, frame, PyTrace_LINE, NULL);
1426  __Pyx_LeaveTracing(tstate);
1427  if (likely(!ret)) {
1428  __Pyx_ErrRestoreInState(tstate, type, value, traceback);
1429  } else {
1430  Py_XDECREF(type);
1431  Py_XDECREF(value);
1432  Py_XDECREF(traceback);
1433  }
1434  return ret;
1435  }
1436  #ifdef WITH_THREAD
1437  #define __Pyx_TraceLine(lineno, nogil, goto_error)\
1438  if (likely(!__Pyx_use_tracing)); else {\
1439  if (nogil) {\
1440  if (CYTHON_TRACE_NOGIL) {\
1441  int ret = 0;\
1442  PyThreadState *tstate;\
1443  PyGILState_STATE state = PyGILState_Ensure();\
1444  tstate = __Pyx_PyThreadState_Current;\
1445  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 0, 0) && tstate->c_tracefunc && __pyx_frame->f_trace) {\
1446  ret = __Pyx_call_line_trace_func(tstate, __pyx_frame, lineno);\
1447  }\
1448  PyGILState_Release(state);\
1449  if (unlikely(ret)) goto_error;\
1450  }\
1451  } else {\
1452  PyThreadState* tstate = __Pyx_PyThreadState_Current;\
1453  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 0, 0) && tstate->c_tracefunc && __pyx_frame->f_trace) {\
1454  int ret = __Pyx_call_line_trace_func(tstate, __pyx_frame, lineno);\
1455  if (unlikely(ret)) goto_error;\
1456  }\
1457  }\
1458  }
1459  #else
1460  #define __Pyx_TraceLine(lineno, nogil, goto_error)\
1461  if (likely(!__Pyx_use_tracing)); else {\
1462  PyThreadState* tstate = __Pyx_PyThreadState_Current;\
1463  if (__Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 0, 0) && tstate->c_tracefunc && __pyx_frame->f_trace) {\
1464  int ret = __Pyx_call_line_trace_func(tstate, __pyx_frame, lineno);\
1465  if (unlikely(ret)) goto_error;\
1466  }\

1748 /* CppExceptionConversion.proto */
1749 #ifndef __Pyx_CppExn2PyErr
1750 #include <new>
1751 #include <typeinfo>
1752 #include <stdexcept>
1753 #include <ios>
1754 static void __Pyx_CppExn2PyErr() {
1755  try {
1756  if (PyErr_Occurred())
1757  ; // let the latest Python exn pass through and ignore the current one
1758  else
1759  throw;
1760  } catch (const std::bad_alloc& exn) {
1761  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_MemoryError, exn.what());
1762  } catch (const std::bad_cast& exn) {
1763  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError, exn.what());
1764  } catch (const std::bad_typeid& exn) {
1765  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError, exn.what());
1766  } catch (const std::domain_error& exn) {
1767  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError, exn.what());
1768  } catch (const std::invalid_argument& exn) {
1769  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError, exn.what());
1770  } catch (const std::ios_base::failure& exn) {
1771  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_IOError, exn.what());
1772  } catch (const std::out_of_range& exn) {
1773  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_IndexError, exn.what());
1774  } catch (const std::overflow_error& exn) {
1775  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_OverflowError, exn.what());
1776  } catch (const std::range_error& exn) {
1777  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ArithmeticError, exn.what());
1778  } catch (const std::underflow_error& exn) {
1779  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ArithmeticError, exn.what());
1780  } catch (const std::exception& exn) {
1781  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, exn.what());
1782  }
1783  catch (...)
1784  {
1785  PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, "Unknown exception");
1786  }
1787 }
1788 #endif

1887 static const char __pyx_k_Trace_of_the_exponential_of_a_m[] = "\n Trace of the exponential of a matrix or linear operator using stochastic\n Lanczos quadrature method.\n\n Given the symmetric matrix or linear operator :math:`\\mathbf{A}` and the\n real exponent :math:`p`, the following is computed:\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathrm{trace} f \\left(\\mathbf{A}^p \\right),\n\n where the function :math:`f` is defined by\n\n .. math::\n\n f(\\lambda) = \\frac{a \\lambda + b}{c \\lambda +d},\n\n provided that :math:`ad - bc \\neq 0`.\n\n If ``gram`` is `True`, then :math:`\\mathbf{A}` in the above is replaced by\n the Gramian matrix :math:`\\mathbf{A}^{\\intercal} \\mathbf{A}`, and the\n following is instead computed:\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathrm{trace} f\n \\left((\\mathbf{A}^{\\intercal}\\mathbf{A})^p \\right).\n\n If :math:`\\mathbf{A} = \\mathbf{A}(t)` is a linear operator of the class\n :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction` with the parameter :math:`t`, then for\n an input tuple :math:`t = (t_1, \\dots, t_q)`, an array output of the\n size :math:`q` is returned, namely:\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathrm{trace} f \\left((\\mathbf{A}(t_i))^p \\right),\n \\quad i=1, \\dots, q.\n\n Parameters\n ----------\n\n A : numpy.ndarray, scipy.sparse, :class:`imate.Matrix`, or :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction`\n A sparse or dense matrix or linear operator. If ``gram`` is `False`,\n then `A` should be symmetric.\n\n .. warning::\n\n The symmetry of `A` is not pre-checked by this function. If\n ``gram`` is `False`, make sure `A` is symmetric.\n\n gram : bool, default=False\n If `True`, the log-determinant of the Gramian matrix,\n :math:`(\\mathbf{A}^{\\intercal}\\mathbf{A})^p`, is computed. The\n Gramian matrix itself is not directly computed. If `False`, the\n log-determinant of :math:`\\mathbf{A}^p` is computed.\n\n p : float, default=1.0\n The real exponent :ma""th:`p` in :math:`\\mathbf{A}^p`.\n\n coeff : (tuple, list, numpy.array), default=[1,0, 0.0, 1.0, 1.0]\n A list, tuple, or array of four float numbers representing the\n coefficients :math:`a`, :math:`b`, :math:`c`, and :math:`d`,\n respectively.\n\n return_info : bool, default=False\n If `True`, this function also returns a dictionary containing\n information about the inner computation, such as process time,\n algorithm settings, etc.\n\n parameters : array_like [`float`], default=one\n This argument is relevant if `A` is a type of\n :class:`AffineMatrixFunction`. By this argument, multiple inquiries,\n :math:`(t_1, \\dots, t_q)`, can be passed to the parameter :math:`t` of\n the linear operator :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t)`. The output of this function\n becomes an array of the size :math:`q` corresponding to each of the\n input matrices :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_i)`.\n\n min_num_samples : int, default=10\n The minimum number of Monte-Carlo samples. If the convergence criterion\n is reached before finishing the minimum number of iterations, the\n iterations are forced to continue till the minimum number of iterations\n is finished. This value should be smaller than\n ``maximum_num_samples``.\n\n max_num_samples : int, default=50\n The maximum number of Monte-Carlo samples. If the convergence criterion\n is not reached by the maximum number of iterations, the iterations are\n forced to stop. This value should be larger than\n ``minimum_num_samples``.\n\n error_atol : float, default=None\n Tolerance of the absolute error of convergence of the output. Once the\n error of convergence reaches ``error_atol + error_rtol * output``, the\n iteration is terminated. If the convergence criterion is not met by the\n tolerance, then the iterations continue till reaching\n ``max_num_samples`` i""terations. If `None`, the termination criterion\n does not depend on this parameter.\n\n error_rtol : float, default=None\n Tolerance of the relative error of convergence of the output. Once the\n error of convergence reaches ``error_atol + error_rtol * output``, the\n iteration is terminated. If the convergence criterion is not met by the\n tolerance, then the iterations continue till reaching\n ``max_num_samples`` iterations. If `None`, the termination criterion\n does not depend on this parameter.\n\n confidence_level : float, default=0.95\n Confidence level of error, which is a number between `0` and `1`. The\n error of convergence of the population of samples is defined by their\n standard deviation times the Z-score, which depends on the confidence\n level. See notes below for details.\n\n outlier_significance_level : float, default=0.001\n One minus the confidence level of the uncertainty of the outliers of\n the output samples. This is a number between `0` and `1`.\n\n lanczos_degree : int, default=20\n The number of Lanczos recursive iterations. The larger Lanczos degree\n leads to better estimation. The computational cost quadratically\n increases with the Lanczos degree.\n\n lanczos_tol : float, default=None\n The tolerance to stop the Lanczos recursive iterations before\n the end of iterations reached. If the tolerance is not met, all the\n iterations (total of ``lanczos_degree`` iterations) continue till the\n end. If set to `None` (default value), the machine' epsilon precision\n is used. The machine's epsilon precision is as follows:\n\n * For 32-bit, machine precision is\n :math:`2^{-23} = 1.1920929 \\times 10^{-7}`.\n * For 64-bit, machine precision is\n :math:`2^{-52} = 2.220446049250313 \\times 10^{-16}`,\n * For 128-bit, machine precision is\n "" :math:`2^{-63} = -1.084202172485504434 \\times 10^{-19}`.\n\n orthogonalize : int, default=0\n Indicates whether to re-orthogonalize the eigenvectors during Lanczos\n recursive iterations.\n\n * If set to `0`, no orthogonalization is performed.\n * If set to a negative integer or an integer larger than\n ``lanczos_degree``, a newly computed eigenvector is orthogonalized\n against all the previous eigenvectors (also known as\n `full reorthogonalization`).\n * If set to a positive integer, say `q`, but less than\n ``lanczos_degree``, the newly computed eigenvector is\n orthogonalized against a window of last `q` previous eigenvectors\n (known as `partial reorthogonalization`).\n\n seed : int, default=None\n A non-negative integer to be used as seed to initiate the generation of\n sequences of peudo-random numbers in the algorithm. This is useful to\n make the result of the randomized algorithm to be reproducible. If\n ``None`` or a negative integer is given, the given seed value is\n ignored and the current processor time is used as the seed to initiate\n he generation random number sequences. In this case, the result is not\n reproducible, rather, is pseudo-random.\n\n num_threads : int, default=0\n Number of processor threads to employ for parallel computation on CPU.\n If set to `0` or a number larger than the available number of threads,\n all threads of the processor are used. The parallelization is performed\n over the Monte-Carlo iterations.\n\n num_gpu_devices : int default=0\n Number of GPU devices (if available) to use for parallel multi-GPU\n processing. If set to `0`, the maximum number of available GPU devices\n is used. This parameter is relevant if ``gpu`` is `True`.\n\n gpu : bool, default=False\n If `True`, the computations are performed on ""GPU devices where the\n number of devices can be set by ``num_gpu_devices``. If no GPU device\n is found, it raises an error.\n\n .. note::\n When performing `repetitive` computation on the same matrix on GPU,\n it is recommended to input `A` as an instance of\n :class:`imate.Matrix` class instead of `numpy` or `scipy` matrices.\n See examples below for clarification.\n\n verbose : bool, default=False\n Prints extra information about the computations.\n\n plot : bool, default=False\n Plots convergence of samples. To this end, `matplotlib` package should\n be installed. If no display is available (such as running this code on\n remote machines), the plots are saved as an `SVG` file in the current\n directory.\n\n Returns\n -------\n\n trlinexp : float or numpy.array\n Log-determinant of `A`. If `A` is of type\n :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction` with an array of ``parameters``,\n then the output is an array.\n\n info : dict\n (Only if ``return_info`` is `True`) A dictionary of information with\n the following.\n\n * ``matrix``:\n * ``data_type``: `str`, {`float32`, `float64`, `float128`}. Type of\n the matrix data.\n * ``gram``: `bool`, whether the matrix `A` or its Gramian is\n considered.\n * ``exponent``: `float`, the exponent `p` in :math:`\\mathbf{A}^p`.\n * ``size``: (int, int) The size of matrix `A`.\n * ``sparse``: `bool`, whether the matrix `A` is sparse or dense.\n * ``nnz``: `int`, if `A` is sparse, the number of non-zero elements\n of `A`.\n * ``density``: `float`, if `A` is sparse, the density of `A`, which\n is the `nnz` divided by size squared.\n * ``num_inquiries``: `int`, the size of inquiries of each parameter\n of the linear operator `A`. I""f `A` is a matrix, this is always\n `1`. If `A` is a type of :class:`AffineMatrixFunction`, this\n value is the number of :math:`t_i` parameters.\n * ``num_operator_parameters``: `int`, number of parameters of the\n operator `A`. If `A` a type of :class:`AffineMatrixFunction`,\n then this value is `1` corresponding to one parameter :math:`t`\n in the affine function `t \\mapsto \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{B}`.\n * ``parameters``: `list` [`float`], the parameters of the linear\n operator `A`.\n\n * ``convergence``:\n * ``all_converged``: `bool`, whether the Monte-Carlo sampling\n converged for all requested parameters :math:`t_i`. If all\n entries of the array for ``converged`` is `True``, then this\n value is also ``True``.\n * ``converged``: `array` [`bool`], whether the Monte-Carlo sampling\n converged for each of the requested parameters :math:`t_i`.\n Convergence is defined based on a termination criterion, such\n as absolute or relative error. If the iterations terminated due\n to reaching the maximum number of samples, this value is `False`.\n * ``min_num_samples``: `int`, the minimum number of Monte-Carlo\n iterations.\n * ``max_num_samples``: `int`, the maximum number of Monte-Carlo\n iterations.\n * ``num_outliers``: `int`, number of outliers found during search\n for outliers among the array of output.\n * ``num_samples_used``: `int`, number of Monte-Carlo samples used\n to produce the output. This is the total number of iterations\n minus the number of outliers.\n * ``samples``: `array` [`float`], an array of the size\n `max_num_samples`. The first few entries (`num_samples_used`) of\n this array ar""e the output results of the Monte-Carlo sampling.\n The average of these samples is the final result. The rest of\n this array is `nan`.\n * ``samples_mean``: `float`, mean of the `samples` array, excluding\n the `nan` values.\n * ``samples_processed_order``: `array` [`int`], in parallel\n processing, samples are processed in non-sequential order. This\n array, which has the same size as `samples`, keeps track of the\n order in which each sample is processed.\n\n * ``error``:\n * ``absolute_error``: `float`, the absolute error of the\n convergence of samples.\n * ``confidence_level``: `float`, the confidence level used to\n calculate the error from standard deviation of samples.\n * ``error_atol``: `float`, the tolerance of absolute error of the\n convergence of samples.\n * ``error_rtol``: `float`, the tolerance of relative error of the\n convergence of samples.\n * ``outlier_significance_level``: `float`, the significance level\n used to determine the outliers in samples.\n * ``relative_error``: `float`, the relative error of the\n convergence of samples.\n\n * ``device``:\n * ``num_cpu_threads``: `int`, number of CPU threads used in shared\n memory parallel processing.\n * ``num_gpu_devices``: `int`, number of GPU devices used in the\n multi-GPU (GPU farm) computation.\n * ``num_gpu_multiprocessors``: `int`, number of GPU\n multi-processors.\n * ``num_gpu_threads_per_multiprocessor``: `int`, number of GPU\n threads on each GPU multi-processor.\n\n * ``time``:\n * ``tot_wall_time``: `float`, total elapsed time of computation.\n * ``alg_wall_time``: `float`, elapsed time of computation dur""ing\n only the algorithm execution.\n * ``cpu_proc_time``: `float`, the CPU processing time of\n computation.\n\n * ``solver``:\n * ``version``: `str`, version of imate.\n * ``method``: 'slq'.\n * ``lanczos_degree``: `bool`, Lanczos degree.\n * ``lanczos_tol``: `float`, Lanczos tolerance.\n * ``orthogonalize``: `int`, orthogonalization flag.\n * ``seed`` : `int`, seed value for random number generation.\n\n Raises\n ------\n\n ImportError\n If the package has not been compiled with GPU support, but ``gpu`` is\n set to `True`. To resolve the issue, set ``gpu`` to `False` to be able\n to use the existing installation. Alternatively, export the\n environment variable ``USE_CUDA=1`` and recompile the source code of\n the package.\n\n See Also\n --------\n\n imate.logdet\n imate.trace\n imate.trlinfrac\n imate.traceinv\n imate.schatten\n\n Notes\n -----\n\n **Computational Complexity:**\n\n This method uses stochastic Lanczos quadrature (SLQ), which is a randomized\n algorithm. The computational complexity of this method is\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathcal{O}((\\rho n^2 + n l) s l),\n\n where :math:`n` is the matrix size, :math:`\\rho` is the density of\n sparse matrix (for dense matrix, :math:`\\rho=1`), :math:`l` is the\n Lanczos degree (set with ``lanczos_degree``), and :math:`s` is the number\n of samples (set with ``min_num_samples`` and ``max_num_samples``).\n\n This method can be used on very large matrices (:math:`n > 2^{12}`). The\n solution is an approximation.\n\n **Input Matrix:**\n\n The input `A` can be either of:\n\n * A matrix, such as `numpy.ndarray`, or `scipy.sparse`.\n * A linear operator representing a matrix using :class:`imate.Matrix`.\n * A linear operator representing a one-parameter family of an affine matrix\n func""tion :math:`t \\mapsto \\mathbf{A} + t\\mathbf{B}` using\n :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction`.\n\n **Output:**\n\n The output is a scalar. However, if `A` is the linear operator\n :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t) = \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{B}` where :math:`t` is\n given as the tuple :math:`t = (t_1, \\dots, t_q)`, then the output of this\n function is an array of size :math:`q` corresponding to the\n race-exponential of each :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_i)`.\n\n .. note::\n\n When `A` represents\n :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t) = \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{I}`, where\n :math:`\\mathbf{I}` is the identity matrix, and :math:`t` is given by\n a tuple :math:`t = (t_1, \\dots, t_q)`, the computational cost of an\n array output of size `q` is the same as computing for a single\n :math:`t_i`. Namely, the trace-exponential of only\n :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_1)` is computed, and the trace-exponential of the\n rest of :math:`i=2, \\dots, q` are obtained from the result of\n :math:`t_1` immediately.\n\n **Algorithm:**\n\n If ``gram`` is `False`, the Lanczos tri-diagonalization method is\n used. This method requires only matrix-vector multiplication. If\n ``gram`` is `True`, the Golub-Kahn bi-diagonalization method is used. This\n method requires both matrix-vector multiplication and transposed-matrix\n vector multiplications.\n\n **Convergence criterion:**\n\n Let :math:`n_{\\min}` and :math:`n_{\\max}` be the minimum and maximum\n number of iterations respectively defined by ``min_num_samples`` and\n ``max_num_samples``. The iterations terminate at\n :math:`n_{\\min} \\leq i \\leq n_{\\max}` where :math:`i` is the\n iteration counter. The iterations stop earlier at :math:`i < n_{\\max}` if\n the convergence error of the mean of the samples is satisfied, as follows.\n\n Suppose :math:`s(j)` and :math:`\\sigma(i)` are respectively the mean and\n standard deviation of samples aft""er :math:`j` iterations. The error of\n convergence, :math:`e(j)`, is defined by\n\n .. math::\n\n e(j) = \\frac{\\sigma(j)}{\\sqrt{j}} Z\n\n where :math:`Z` is the Z-score defined by\n\n .. math::\n\n Z = \\sqrt{2} \\mathrm{erf}^{-1}(\\phi).\n\n In the above, :math:`\\phi` is the confidence level and set by\n ``confidence_level`` argument, and :math:`\\mathrm{erf}^{-1}` is the\n inverse error function. A confidence level of 95%, for instance, means that\n the Z-score is 1.96, which means the confidence interval is\n :math:`\\pm 1.96 \\sigma`.\n\n The termination criterion is\n\n .. math::\n\n e(j) < \\epsilon_a + s(j) \\epsilon_r,\n\n where :math:`\\epsilon_{a}` and :math:`\\epsilon_r` are the absolute and\n relative error tolerances respectively, and they are set by ``error_atol``\n and ``error_rtol``.\n\n **Convergence for the case of multiple parameters:**\n\n When `A` is a type of :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction` representing the\n affine matrix function :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t) = \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{B}`\n and if multiple parameters :math:`t_i`, :math:`i=1,\\dots, q` are passed to\n this function through ``parameters`` argument, the convergence criterion\n has to be satisfied for each of :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_i)`. Specifically, the\n iterations are terminated as follows:\n\n * If :math:`\\mathbf{B}` is the identity matrix, iterations for all\n :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_i)` continue till the convergence criterion for\n *all* :math:`t_i` are satisfied. That is, even if :math:`t=t_i` is\n converged but :math:`t=t_j` has not converged yet, the iterations for\n :math:`t=t_i` will continue.\n :\n * If :math:`\\mathbf{B}` is not the identity matrix, the iterations for\n each of :math:`t_i` are independent. That is, if :math:`t=t_i` converges,\n the iterations for that parameter will stop regardless of the convergence\n status of other parame""ters.\n\n **Plotting:**\n\n If ``plot`` is set to `True`, it plots the convergence of samples and their\n relative error.\n\n * If no graphical backend exists (such as running the code on a remote\n server or manually disabling the X11 backend), the plot will not be\n shown, rather, it will be saved as an ``svg`` file in the current\n directory.\n * If the executable ``latex`` is available on ``PATH``, the plot is\n rendered using :math:`\\rm\\LaTeX` and it may take slightly longer to\n produce the plot.\n * If :math:`\\rm\\LaTeX` is not installed, it uses any available San-Serif\n font to render the plot.\n\n To manually disable interactive plot display and save the plot as\n ``svg`` instead, add the following at the very beginning of your code\n before importing :mod:`imate`:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> import os\n >>> os.environ['IMATE_NO_DISPLAY'] = 'True'\n\n References\n ----------\n\n * `Ubaru, S., Chen, J., and Saad, Y. (2017)\n <https://www-users.cs.umn.edu/~saad/PDF/ys-2016-04.pdf>`_,\n Fast Estimation of :math:`\\mathrm{tr}(F(A))` Via Stochastic Lanczos\n Quadrature, SIAM J. Matrix Anal. Appl., 38(4), 1075-1099.\n\n Examples\n --------\n\n **Symmetric Input Matrix:**\n\n The `slq` method requires the input matrix of :func:`imate.trlinfrac` function\n to be symmetric when ``gram`` is `False`. For the first example, generate a\n symmetric sample matrix using :func:`imate.toeplitz` function as follows:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Import packages\n >>> from imate import toeplitz\n\n >>> # Generate a symmetric matrix by setting gram=True.\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=100, gram=True)\n\n In the above, by passing ``gram=True`` to :func:`imate.toeplitz` function,\n the Gramian of the Toeplitz matrix is returned, which is symmetric. Compute\n the race-exponential of :math:`\\mathbf{A}^{2.5}`:""\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Import packages\n >>> from imate import trlinfrac\n\n >>> # Compute the trace-exponential\n >>> trlinfrac(A, gram=False, p=2.5, method='slq')\n 277.00578301560057\n\n .. note:\n\n Since `slq` is a stochastic method, the above result slightly\n differs after each run.\n\n **Gramian Matrix:**\n\n Passing ``gram=True`` to :func:`imate.trlinfrac` function uses the Gramian\n of the input matrix. n this case, the input matrix can be non-symmetric.\n In the next example, generate a non-symmetric matrix, :math:`\\mathbf{B}`,\n then compute the trace-exponential of\n :math:`(\\mathbf{B}^{\\intercal} \\mathbf{B})^{2.5}`.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Generate a non-symmetric matrix by setting gram=False\n >>> B = toeplitz(2, 1, size=100, gram=False)\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Gramian by passing gram=True\n >>> trlinfrac(B, gram=True, p=2.5, method='slq')\n 275.15518680196476\n\n Note that the result of the two examples in the above are the similar since\n the input matrix :math:`\\mathbf{A}` of the first example is the Gramian of\n the input matrix :math:`\\mathbf{B}` in the second example, that is\n :math:`\\mathbf{A} = \\mathbf{B}^{\\intercal} \\mathbf{B}`. Since the\n second example uses the Gramian of the input matrix, it computes the same\n quantity as the first example.\n\n **Verbose output:**\n\n By setting ``verbose`` to `True`, useful info about the process is\n printed.\n\n .. literalinclude:: ../_static/data/imate.trlinfrac.slq-verbose-1.txt\n :language: python\n\n **Output information:**\n\n Print information about the inner computation:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> ld, info = trlinfrac(A, method='slq', return_info=True)\n >>> print(ld)\n 138.6294361119891\n\n >>> # Print dictionary neatly using pprint\n >>> from ""pprint import pprint\n >>> pprint(info)\n {\n 'matrix': {\n 'data_type': b'float64',\n 'density': 0.0298,\n 'exponent': 1.0,\n 'gram': False,\n 'nnz': 298,\n 'num_inquiries': 1,\n 'num_operator_parameters': 0,\n 'parameters': None,\n 'size': (100, 100),\n 'sparse': True\n },\n 'convergence': {\n 'all_converged': False,\n 'converged': False,\n 'max_num_samples': 50,\n 'min_num_samples': 10,\n 'num_outliers': 0,\n 'num_samples_used': 50,\n 'samples': array([124.65021242, ..., 143.27314446]),\n 'samples_mean': 139.89509513079338,\n 'samples_processed_order': array([ 4, ..., 47])\n },\n 'error': {\n 'absolute_error': 2.345203485787551,\n 'confidence_level': 0.95,\n 'error_atol': 0.0,\n 'error_rtol': 0.01,\n 'outlier_significance_level': 0.001,\n 'relative_error': 0.01676401508998531\n },\n 'solver': {\n 'lanczos_degree': 20,\n 'lanczos_tol': 2.220446049250313e-16,\n 'method': 'slq',\n 'orthogonalize': 0,\n 'seed': None,\n 'version': '0.15.0'\n },\n 'device': {\n 'num_cpu_threads': 8,\n 'num_gpu_devices': 0,\n 'num_gpu_multiprocessors': 0,\n 'num_gpu_threads_per_multiprocessor': 0\n },\n 'time': {\n 'alg_wall_time': 0.002254009246826172,\n 'cpu_proc_time': 0.01330678200000035,\n 'tot_wall_time': 0.0023698790464550257\n }\n }\n\n **Large matrix:**\n\n Compute th""e trace-exponential of a very large sparse matrix using at least\n `100` samples:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n :emphasize-lines: 6, 7\n\n >>> # Generate a matrix of size one million\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=1000000, gram=True)\n\n >>> # Approximate trace-exponential using stochastic Lanczos quadrature\n >>> # with at least 100 Monte-Carlo sampling\n >>> ld, info = trlinfrac(A, method='slq', min_num_samples=100,\n ... max_num_samples=200, return_info=True)\n >>> print(ld)\n 1386320.4734751645\n\n >>> # Find the time it took to compute the above\n >>> print(info['time'])\n {\n 'tot_wall_time': 16.598053652094677,\n 'alg_wall_time': 16.57977867126465,\n 'cpu_proc_time': 113.03275911399999\n }\n\n **Plotting:**\n\n By setting ``plot`` to `True`, plots of samples during Monte-Carlo\n iterations and the convergence of their mean are generated.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=1000000, gram=True)\n >>> trlinfrac(A, method='slq', min_num_samples=20, max_num_samples=80,\n ... error_rtol=2e-4, confidence_level=0.95,\n ... outlier_significance_level=0.001, plot=True)\n\n .. image:: ../_static/images/plots/trlinfrac_slq_convergence_1.png\n :align: center\n :class: custom-dark\n\n In the left plot, the samples are shown in circles and the cumulative mean\n of the samples is shown by a solid black curve. The shaded area corresponds\n to the 95% confidence interval :math:`\\pm 1.96 \\sigma`, which is set by\n ``confidence_level=0.95``. The samples outside the interval of 99.9% are\n considered outliers, which is set by the significance level\n ``outlier_significance_level=0.001``.\n\n In the right plot, the darker shaded area in the interval :math:`[0, 20]`\n shows the minimum number of samples and is set by ``min_""num_samples=20``.\n The iterations do not stop till the minimum number of iterations is passed.\n We can observe that sampling is terminated after 55 iterations where the\n relative error of samples reaches 0.02% since we set ``error_rtol=2e-4``.\n The lighter shaded area in the interval :math:`[56, 80]` corresponds to the\n iterations that were not performed to reach the specified maximum\n iterations by ``max_num_samples=80``.\n\n **Matrix operator:**\n\n Use an object of :class:`imate.Matrix` class as an alternative method to\n pass the matrix `A` to the `trlinfrac` function.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n :emphasize-lines: 8\n\n >>> # Import matrix operator\n >>> from imate import toeplitz, trlinfrac, Matrix\n\n >>> # Generate a sample matrix (a toeplitz matrix)\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=100, gram=True)\n\n >>> # Create a matrix operator object from matrix A\n >>> Aop = Matrix(A)\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Aop\n >>> trlinfrac(Aop, method='slq')\n 141.52929878934194\n\n An advantage of passing `Aop` (instead of `A`) to the `trlinfrac` function\n will be clear when using GPU.\n\n **Computation on GPU:**\n\n The argument ``gpu=True`` performs the computations on GPU. The following\n example uses the object `Aop` created earlier.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Aop\n >>> trlinfrac(Aop, method='slq', gpu=True)\n 141.52929878934194\n\n The above function call triggers the object `Aop` to automatically load the\n matrix data on the GPU.\n\n One could have used `A` instead of `Aop` in the above. However, an\n advantage of using `Aop` (instead of the matrix `A` directly) is that by\n calling the above `trlinfrac` function (or another function) again on this\n matrix, the data of this matrix does not have to be re-allocated on the GPU\n device again. To highlight this"" point, call the above function again, but\n this time, set ``gram`` to `True` to compute something different.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Aop\n >>> trlinfrac(Aop, method='slq', gpu=True, gram=True)\n 141.52929878934194\n\n In the above example, no data is needed to be transferred from CPU host to\n GPU device again. However, if `A` was used instead of `Aop`, the data would\n have been transferred from CPU to GPU again for the second time. The `Aop`\n object holds the data on GPU for later use as long as this object does no\n go out of the scope of the python environment. Once the variable `Aop` goes\n out of scope, the matrix data on all the GPU devices will be cleaned\n automatically.\n\n **Affine matrix operator:**\n\n Use an object of :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction` to create the linear\n operator\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathbf{A}(t) = \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{I}.\n\n The object :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t)` can be passed to `trlinfrac` function with\n multiple values for the parameter :math:`t` to compute their\n trace-exponential all at once, as follows.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n :emphasize-lines: 8\n\n >>> # Import affine matrix function\n >>> from imate import toeplitz, trlinfrac, AffineMatrixFunction\n\n >>> # Generate a sample matrix (a toeplitz matrix)\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=100, gram=True)\n\n >>> # Create a matrix operator object from matrix A\n >>> Aop = AffineMatrixFunction(A)\n\n >>> # A list of parameters t to pass to Aop\n >>> t = [-1.0, 0.0, 1.0]\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Aop for all parameters t\n >>> trlinfrac(Aop, method='slq', parameters=t, min_num_samples=20,\n ... max_num_samples=80, error_rtol=1e-3, confidence_level=0.95,\n ... outlier_significance_level=0.001, plot=True, verbose=True)\n array([ 68.714""11681, 135.88356906, 163.44156683])\n\n The output of the verbose argument is shown below. In the results section\n of the table below, each row `i` under the `inquiry` column corresponds to\n each element of the parameters ``t = [-1, 0, 1]`` that was specified by\n ``parameters`` argument.\n\n .. literalinclude:: ../_static/data/imate.trlinfrac.slq-verbose-2.txt\n :language: python\n\n The output of the plot is shown below. Each colored curve corresponds to\n a parameter in ``t = [-1, 0, 1]``.\n\n .. image:: ../_static/images/plots/trlinfrac_slq_convergence_2.png\n :align: center\n :width: 80%\n :class: custom-dark\n ";

2089 static char __pyx_doc_5imate_9trlinfrac_11_slq_method_slq_method[] = "slq_method(A, gram=False, p=1.0, coeff=[1.0, 0.0, 1.0, 1.0], return_info=False, parameters=None, min_num_samples=10, max_num_samples=50, error_atol=None, error_rtol=1e-2, confidence_level=0.95, outlier_significance_level=0.001, lanczos_degree=20, lanczos_tol=None, orthogonalize=0, seed=None, num_threads=0, num_gpu_devices=0, gpu=False, verbose=False, plot=False)\n\n Trace of the exponential of a matrix or linear operator using stochastic\n Lanczos quadrature method.\n\n Given the symmetric matrix or linear operator :math:`\\mathbf{A}` and the\n real exponent :math:`p`, the following is computed:\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathrm{trace} f \\left(\\mathbf{A}^p \\right),\n\n where the function :math:`f` is defined by\n\n .. math::\n\n f(\\lambda) = \\frac{a \\lambda + b}{c \\lambda +d},\n\n provided that :math:`ad - bc \\neq 0`.\n\n If ``gram`` is `True`, then :math:`\\mathbf{A}` in the above is replaced by\n the Gramian matrix :math:`\\mathbf{A}^{\\intercal} \\mathbf{A}`, and the\n following is instead computed:\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathrm{trace} f\n \\left((\\mathbf{A}^{\\intercal}\\mathbf{A})^p \\right).\n\n If :math:`\\mathbf{A} = \\mathbf{A}(t)` is a linear operator of the class\n :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction` with the parameter :math:`t`, then for\n an input tuple :math:`t = (t_1, \\dots, t_q)`, an array output of the\n size :math:`q` is returned, namely:\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathrm{trace} f \\left((\\mathbf{A}(t_i))^p \\right),\n \\quad i=1, \\dots, q.\n\n Parameters\n ----------\n\n A : numpy.ndarray, scipy.sparse, :class:`imate.Matrix`, or :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction`\n A sparse or dense matrix or linear operator. If ``gram`` is `False`,\n then `A` should be symmetric.\n\n .. warning::\n\n The symmetry of `A` is not pre-checked by this function. If\n ``gram`` is `False`, make sure `A` is symmetric.""\n\n gram : bool, default=False\n If `True`, the log-determinant of the Gramian matrix,\n :math:`(\\mathbf{A}^{\\intercal}\\mathbf{A})^p`, is computed. The\n Gramian matrix itself is not directly computed. If `False`, the\n log-determinant of :math:`\\mathbf{A}^p` is computed.\n\n p : float, default=1.0\n The real exponent :math:`p` in :math:`\\mathbf{A}^p`.\n\n coeff : (tuple, list, numpy.array), default=[1,0, 0.0, 1.0, 1.0]\n A list, tuple, or array of four float numbers representing the\n coefficients :math:`a`, :math:`b`, :math:`c`, and :math:`d`,\n respectively.\n\n return_info : bool, default=False\n If `True`, this function also returns a dictionary containing\n information about the inner computation, such as process time,\n algorithm settings, etc.\n\n parameters : array_like [`float`], default=one\n This argument is relevant if `A` is a type of\n :class:`AffineMatrixFunction`. By this argument, multiple inquiries,\n :math:`(t_1, \\dots, t_q)`, can be passed to the parameter :math:`t` of\n the linear operator :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t)`. The output of this function\n becomes an array of the size :math:`q` corresponding to each of the\n input matrices :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_i)`.\n\n min_num_samples : int, default=10\n The minimum number of Monte-Carlo samples. If the convergence criterion\n is reached before finishing the minimum number of iterations, the\n iterations are forced to continue till the minimum number of iterations\n is finished. This value should be smaller than\n ``maximum_num_samples``.\n\n max_num_samples : int, default=50\n The maximum number of Monte-Carlo samples. If the convergence criterion\n is not reached by the maximum number of iterations, the iterations are\n forced to stop. This value should be larger than\n ``minimum_num_samples``.\n""\n error_atol : float, default=None\n Tolerance of the absolute error of convergence of the output. Once the\n error of convergence reaches ``error_atol + error_rtol * output``, the\n iteration is terminated. If the convergence criterion is not met by the\n tolerance, then the iterations continue till reaching\n ``max_num_samples`` iterations. If `None`, the termination criterion\n does not depend on this parameter.\n\n error_rtol : float, default=None\n Tolerance of the relative error of convergence of the output. Once the\n error of convergence reaches ``error_atol + error_rtol * output``, the\n iteration is terminated. If the convergence criterion is not met by the\n tolerance, then the iterations continue till reaching\n ``max_num_samples`` iterations. If `None`, the termination criterion\n does not depend on this parameter.\n\n confidence_level : float, default=0.95\n Confidence level of error, which is a number between `0` and `1`. The\n error of convergence of the population of samples is defined by their\n standard deviation times the Z-score, which depends on the confidence\n level. See notes below for details.\n\n outlier_significance_level : float, default=0.001\n One minus the confidence level of the uncertainty of the outliers of\n the output samples. This is a number between `0` and `1`.\n\n lanczos_degree : int, default=20\n The number of Lanczos recursive iterations. The larger Lanczos degree\n leads to better estimation. The computational cost quadratically\n increases with the Lanczos degree.\n\n lanczos_tol : float, default=None\n The tolerance to stop the Lanczos recursive iterations before\n the end of iterations reached. If the tolerance is not met, all the\n iterations (total of ``lanczos_degree`` iterations) continue till the\n end. If set to `None` (de""fault value), the machine' epsilon precision\n is used. The machine's epsilon precision is as follows:\n\n * For 32-bit, machine precision is\n :math:`2^{-23} = 1.1920929 \\times 10^{-7}`.\n * For 64-bit, machine precision is\n :math:`2^{-52} = 2.220446049250313 \\times 10^{-16}`,\n * For 128-bit, machine precision is\n :math:`2^{-63} = -1.084202172485504434 \\times 10^{-19}`.\n\n orthogonalize : int, default=0\n Indicates whether to re-orthogonalize the eigenvectors during Lanczos\n recursive iterations.\n\n * If set to `0`, no orthogonalization is performed.\n * If set to a negative integer or an integer larger than\n ``lanczos_degree``, a newly computed eigenvector is orthogonalized\n against all the previous eigenvectors (also known as\n `full reorthogonalization`).\n * If set to a positive integer, say `q`, but less than\n ``lanczos_degree``, the newly computed eigenvector is\n orthogonalized against a window of last `q` previous eigenvectors\n (known as `partial reorthogonalization`).\n\n seed : int, default=None\n A non-negative integer to be used as seed to initiate the generation of\n sequences of peudo-random numbers in the algorithm. This is useful to\n make the result of the randomized algorithm to be reproducible. If\n ``None`` or a negative integer is given, the given seed value is\n ignored and the current processor time is used as the seed to initiate\n he generation random number sequences. In this case, the result is not\n reproducible, rather, is pseudo-random.\n\n num_threads : int, default=0\n Number of processor threads to employ for parallel computation on CPU.\n If set to `0` or a number larger than the available number of threads,\n all threads of the processor are used. The parallelization is performed\n over the ""Monte-Carlo iterations.\n\n num_gpu_devices : int default=0\n Number of GPU devices (if available) to use for parallel multi-GPU\n processing. If set to `0`, the maximum number of available GPU devices\n is used. This parameter is relevant if ``gpu`` is `True`.\n\n gpu : bool, default=False\n If `True`, the computations are performed on GPU devices where the\n number of devices can be set by ``num_gpu_devices``. If no GPU device\n is found, it raises an error.\n\n .. note::\n When performing `repetitive` computation on the same matrix on GPU,\n it is recommended to input `A` as an instance of\n :class:`imate.Matrix` class instead of `numpy` or `scipy` matrices.\n See examples below for clarification.\n\n verbose : bool, default=False\n Prints extra information about the computations.\n\n plot : bool, default=False\n Plots convergence of samples. To this end, `matplotlib` package should\n be installed. If no display is available (such as running this code on\n remote machines), the plots are saved as an `SVG` file in the current\n directory.\n\n Returns\n -------\n\n trlinexp : float or numpy.array\n Log-determinant of `A`. If `A` is of type\n :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction` with an array of ``parameters``,\n then the output is an array.\n\n info : dict\n (Only if ``return_info`` is `True`) A dictionary of information with\n the following.\n\n * ``matrix``:\n * ``data_type``: `str`, {`float32`, `float64`, `float128`}. Type of\n the matrix data.\n * ``gram``: `bool`, whether the matrix `A` or its Gramian is\n considered.\n * ``exponent``: `float`, the exponent `p` in :math:`\\mathbf{A}^p`.\n * ``size``: (int, int) The size of matrix `A`.\n * ``sparse``: `bool`, whether the matrix `A` is sparse ""or dense.\n * ``nnz``: `int`, if `A` is sparse, the number of non-zero elements\n of `A`.\n * ``density``: `float`, if `A` is sparse, the density of `A`, which\n is the `nnz` divided by size squared.\n * ``num_inquiries``: `int`, the size of inquiries of each parameter\n of the linear operator `A`. If `A` is a matrix, this is always\n `1`. If `A` is a type of :class:`AffineMatrixFunction`, this\n value is the number of :math:`t_i` parameters.\n * ``num_operator_parameters``: `int`, number of parameters of the\n operator `A`. If `A` a type of :class:`AffineMatrixFunction`,\n then this value is `1` corresponding to one parameter :math:`t`\n in the affine function `t \\mapsto \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{B}`.\n * ``parameters``: `list` [`float`], the parameters of the linear\n operator `A`.\n\n * ``convergence``:\n * ``all_converged``: `bool`, whether the Monte-Carlo sampling\n converged for all requested parameters :math:`t_i`. If all\n entries of the array for ``converged`` is `True``, then this\n value is also ``True``.\n * ``converged``: `array` [`bool`], whether the Monte-Carlo sampling\n converged for each of the requested parameters :math:`t_i`.\n Convergence is defined based on a termination criterion, such\n as absolute or relative error. If the iterations terminated due\n to reaching the maximum number of samples, this value is `False`.\n * ``min_num_samples``: `int`, the minimum number of Monte-Carlo\n iterations.\n * ``max_num_samples``: `int`, the maximum number of Monte-Carlo\n iterations.\n * ``num_outliers``: `int`, number of outliers found during search\n for outliers among the array of output.\n "" * ``num_samples_used``: `int`, number of Monte-Carlo samples used\n to produce the output. This is the total number of iterations\n minus the number of outliers.\n * ``samples``: `array` [`float`], an array of the size\n `max_num_samples`. The first few entries (`num_samples_used`) of\n this array are the output results of the Monte-Carlo sampling.\n The average of these samples is the final result. The rest of\n this array is `nan`.\n * ``samples_mean``: `float`, mean of the `samples` array, excluding\n the `nan` values.\n * ``samples_processed_order``: `array` [`int`], in parallel\n processing, samples are processed in non-sequential order. This\n array, which has the same size as `samples`, keeps track of the\n order in which each sample is processed.\n\n * ``error``:\n * ``absolute_error``: `float`, the absolute error of the\n convergence of samples.\n * ``confidence_level``: `float`, the confidence level used to\n calculate the error from standard deviation of samples.\n * ``error_atol``: `float`, the tolerance of absolute error of the\n convergence of samples.\n * ``error_rtol``: `float`, the tolerance of relative error of the\n convergence of samples.\n * ``outlier_significance_level``: `float`, the significance level\n used to determine the outliers in samples.\n * ``relative_error``: `float`, the relative error of the\n convergence of samples.\n\n * ``device``:\n * ``num_cpu_threads``: `int`, number of CPU threads used in shared\n memory parallel processing.\n * ``num_gpu_devices``: `int`, number of GPU devices used in the\n multi-GPU (GPU farm) computation.\n * ``num_gpu_mul""tiprocessors``: `int`, number of GPU\n multi-processors.\n * ``num_gpu_threads_per_multiprocessor``: `int`, number of GPU\n threads on each GPU multi-processor.\n\n * ``time``:\n * ``tot_wall_time``: `float`, total elapsed time of computation.\n * ``alg_wall_time``: `float`, elapsed time of computation during\n only the algorithm execution.\n * ``cpu_proc_time``: `float`, the CPU processing time of\n computation.\n\n * ``solver``:\n * ``version``: `str`, version of imate.\n * ``method``: 'slq'.\n * ``lanczos_degree``: `bool`, Lanczos degree.\n * ``lanczos_tol``: `float`, Lanczos tolerance.\n * ``orthogonalize``: `int`, orthogonalization flag.\n * ``seed`` : `int`, seed value for random number generation.\n\n Raises\n ------\n\n ImportError\n If the package has not been compiled with GPU support, but ``gpu`` is\n set to `True`. To resolve the issue, set ``gpu`` to `False` to be able\n to use the existing installation. Alternatively, export the\n environment variable ``USE_CUDA=1`` and recompile the source code of\n the package.\n\n See Also\n --------\n\n imate.logdet\n imate.trace\n imate.trlinfrac\n imate.traceinv\n imate.schatten\n\n Notes\n -----\n\n **Computational Complexity:**\n\n This method uses stochastic Lanczos quadrature (SLQ), which is a randomized\n algorithm. The computational complexity of this method is\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathcal{O}((\\rho n^2 + n l) s l),\n\n where :math:`n` is the matrix size, :math:`\\rho` is the density of\n sparse matrix (for dense matrix, :math:`\\rho=1`), :math:`l` is the\n Lanczos degree (set with ``lanczos_degree``), and :math:`s` is the number\n of samples (set with ``min_num_samples`` and ``max_num_samples``).\n\n This method can be used on ver""y large matrices (:math:`n > 2^{12}`). The\n solution is an approximation.\n\n **Input Matrix:**\n\n The input `A` can be either of:\n\n * A matrix, such as `numpy.ndarray`, or `scipy.sparse`.\n * A linear operator representing a matrix using :class:`imate.Matrix`.\n * A linear operator representing a one-parameter family of an affine matrix\n function :math:`t \\mapsto \\mathbf{A} + t\\mathbf{B}` using\n :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction`.\n\n **Output:**\n\n The output is a scalar. However, if `A` is the linear operator\n :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t) = \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{B}` where :math:`t` is\n given as the tuple :math:`t = (t_1, \\dots, t_q)`, then the output of this\n function is an array of size :math:`q` corresponding to the\n race-exponential of each :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_i)`.\n\n .. note::\n\n When `A` represents\n :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t) = \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{I}`, where\n :math:`\\mathbf{I}` is the identity matrix, and :math:`t` is given by\n a tuple :math:`t = (t_1, \\dots, t_q)`, the computational cost of an\n array output of size `q` is the same as computing for a single\n :math:`t_i`. Namely, the trace-exponential of only\n :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_1)` is computed, and the trace-exponential of the\n rest of :math:`i=2, \\dots, q` are obtained from the result of\n :math:`t_1` immediately.\n\n **Algorithm:**\n\n If ``gram`` is `False`, the Lanczos tri-diagonalization method is\n used. This method requires only matrix-vector multiplication. If\n ``gram`` is `True`, the Golub-Kahn bi-diagonalization method is used. This\n method requires both matrix-vector multiplication and transposed-matrix\n vector multiplications.\n\n **Convergence criterion:**\n\n Let :math:`n_{\\min}` and :math:`n_{\\max}` be the minimum and maximum\n number of iterations respectively defined by ``min_num_samples`` and\n ``max_num_samples``. The ""iterations terminate at\n :math:`n_{\\min} \\leq i \\leq n_{\\max}` where :math:`i` is the\n iteration counter. The iterations stop earlier at :math:`i < n_{\\max}` if\n the convergence error of the mean of the samples is satisfied, as follows.\n\n Suppose :math:`s(j)` and :math:`\\sigma(i)` are respectively the mean and\n standard deviation of samples after :math:`j` iterations. The error of\n convergence, :math:`e(j)`, is defined by\n\n .. math::\n\n e(j) = \\frac{\\sigma(j)}{\\sqrt{j}} Z\n\n where :math:`Z` is the Z-score defined by\n\n .. math::\n\n Z = \\sqrt{2} \\mathrm{erf}^{-1}(\\phi).\n\n In the above, :math:`\\phi` is the confidence level and set by\n ``confidence_level`` argument, and :math:`\\mathrm{erf}^{-1}` is the\n inverse error function. A confidence level of 95%, for instance, means that\n the Z-score is 1.96, which means the confidence interval is\n :math:`\\pm 1.96 \\sigma`.\n\n The termination criterion is\n\n .. math::\n\n e(j) < \\epsilon_a + s(j) \\epsilon_r,\n\n where :math:`\\epsilon_{a}` and :math:`\\epsilon_r` are the absolute and\n relative error tolerances respectively, and they are set by ``error_atol``\n and ``error_rtol``.\n\n **Convergence for the case of multiple parameters:**\n\n When `A` is a type of :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction` representing the\n affine matrix function :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t) = \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{B}`\n and if multiple parameters :math:`t_i`, :math:`i=1,\\dots, q` are passed to\n this function through ``parameters`` argument, the convergence criterion\n has to be satisfied for each of :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_i)`. Specifically, the\n iterations are terminated as follows:\n\n * If :math:`\\mathbf{B}` is the identity matrix, iterations for all\n :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t_i)` continue till the convergence criterion for\n *all* :math:`t_i` are satisfied. That is, even if :math:`t=t_i` is\n converged ""but :math:`t=t_j` has not converged yet, the iterations for\n :math:`t=t_i` will continue.\n :\n * If :math:`\\mathbf{B}` is not the identity matrix, the iterations for\n each of :math:`t_i` are independent. That is, if :math:`t=t_i` converges,\n the iterations for that parameter will stop regardless of the convergence\n status of other parameters.\n\n **Plotting:**\n\n If ``plot`` is set to `True`, it plots the convergence of samples and their\n relative error.\n\n * If no graphical backend exists (such as running the code on a remote\n server or manually disabling the X11 backend), the plot will not be\n shown, rather, it will be saved as an ``svg`` file in the current\n directory.\n * If the executable ``latex`` is available on ``PATH``, the plot is\n rendered using :math:`\\rm\\LaTeX` and it may take slightly longer to\n produce the plot.\n * If :math:`\\rm\\LaTeX` is not installed, it uses any available San-Serif\n font to render the plot.\n\n To manually disable interactive plot display and save the plot as\n ``svg`` instead, add the following at the very beginning of your code\n before importing :mod:`imate`:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> import os\n >>> os.environ['IMATE_NO_DISPLAY'] = 'True'\n\n References\n ----------\n\n * `Ubaru, S., Chen, J., and Saad, Y. (2017)\n <https://www-users.cs.umn.edu/~saad/PDF/ys-2016-04.pdf>`_,\n Fast Estimation of :math:`\\mathrm{tr}(F(A))` Via Stochastic Lanczos\n Quadrature, SIAM J. Matrix Anal. Appl., 38(4), 1075-1099.\n\n Examples\n --------\n\n **Symmetric Input Matrix:**\n\n The `slq` method requires the input matrix of :func:`imate.trlinfrac` function\n to be symmetric when ``gram`` is `False`. For the first example, generate a\n symmetric sample matrix using :func:`imate.toeplitz` function as follows:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Import packages\n "" >>> from imate import toeplitz\n\n >>> # Generate a symmetric matrix by setting gram=True.\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=100, gram=True)\n\n In the above, by passing ``gram=True`` to :func:`imate.toeplitz` function,\n the Gramian of the Toeplitz matrix is returned, which is symmetric. Compute\n the race-exponential of :math:`\\mathbf{A}^{2.5}`:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Import packages\n >>> from imate import trlinfrac\n\n >>> # Compute the trace-exponential\n >>> trlinfrac(A, gram=False, p=2.5, method='slq')\n 277.00578301560057\n\n .. note:\n\n Since `slq` is a stochastic method, the above result slightly\n differs after each run.\n\n **Gramian Matrix:**\n\n Passing ``gram=True`` to :func:`imate.trlinfrac` function uses the Gramian\n of the input matrix. n this case, the input matrix can be non-symmetric.\n In the next example, generate a non-symmetric matrix, :math:`\\mathbf{B}`,\n then compute the trace-exponential of\n :math:`(\\mathbf{B}^{\\intercal} \\mathbf{B})^{2.5}`.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Generate a non-symmetric matrix by setting gram=False\n >>> B = toeplitz(2, 1, size=100, gram=False)\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Gramian by passing gram=True\n >>> trlinfrac(B, gram=True, p=2.5, method='slq')\n 275.15518680196476\n\n Note that the result of the two examples in the above are the similar since\n the input matrix :math:`\\mathbf{A}` of the first example is the Gramian of\n the input matrix :math:`\\mathbf{B}` in the second example, that is\n :math:`\\mathbf{A} = \\mathbf{B}^{\\intercal} \\mathbf{B}`. Since the\n second example uses the Gramian of the input matrix, it computes the same\n quantity as the first example.\n\n **Verbose output:**\n\n By setting ``verbose`` to `True`, useful info about the process is\n printed.\n\n .. literalinclude:: ../_static/dat""a/imate.trlinfrac.slq-verbose-1.txt\n :language: python\n\n **Output information:**\n\n Print information about the inner computation:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> ld, info = trlinfrac(A, method='slq', return_info=True)\n >>> print(ld)\n 138.6294361119891\n\n >>> # Print dictionary neatly using pprint\n >>> from pprint import pprint\n >>> pprint(info)\n {\n 'matrix': {\n 'data_type': b'float64',\n 'density': 0.0298,\n 'exponent': 1.0,\n 'gram': False,\n 'nnz': 298,\n 'num_inquiries': 1,\n 'num_operator_parameters': 0,\n 'parameters': None,\n 'size': (100, 100),\n 'sparse': True\n },\n 'convergence': {\n 'all_converged': False,\n 'converged': False,\n 'max_num_samples': 50,\n 'min_num_samples': 10,\n 'num_outliers': 0,\n 'num_samples_used': 50,\n 'samples': array([124.65021242, ..., 143.27314446]),\n 'samples_mean': 139.89509513079338,\n 'samples_processed_order': array([ 4, ..., 47])\n },\n 'error': {\n 'absolute_error': 2.345203485787551,\n 'confidence_level': 0.95,\n 'error_atol': 0.0,\n 'error_rtol': 0.01,\n 'outlier_significance_level': 0.001,\n 'relative_error': 0.01676401508998531\n },\n 'solver': {\n 'lanczos_degree': 20,\n 'lanczos_tol': 2.220446049250313e-16,\n 'method': 'slq',\n 'orthogonalize': 0,\n 'seed': None,\n 'version': '0.15.0'\n },\n 'device': {\n 'num_cpu_threads': 8,\n 'num_gpu_devices': 0,\n "" 'num_gpu_multiprocessors': 0,\n 'num_gpu_threads_per_multiprocessor': 0\n },\n 'time': {\n 'alg_wall_time': 0.002254009246826172,\n 'cpu_proc_time': 0.01330678200000035,\n 'tot_wall_time': 0.0023698790464550257\n }\n }\n\n **Large matrix:**\n\n Compute the trace-exponential of a very large sparse matrix using at least\n `100` samples:\n\n .. code-block:: python\n :emphasize-lines: 6, 7\n\n >>> # Generate a matrix of size one million\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=1000000, gram=True)\n\n >>> # Approximate trace-exponential using stochastic Lanczos quadrature\n >>> # with at least 100 Monte-Carlo sampling\n >>> ld, info = trlinfrac(A, method='slq', min_num_samples=100,\n ... max_num_samples=200, return_info=True)\n >>> print(ld)\n 1386320.4734751645\n\n >>> # Find the time it took to compute the above\n >>> print(info['time'])\n {\n 'tot_wall_time': 16.598053652094677,\n 'alg_wall_time': 16.57977867126465,\n 'cpu_proc_time': 113.03275911399999\n }\n\n **Plotting:**\n\n By setting ``plot`` to `True`, plots of samples during Monte-Carlo\n iterations and the convergence of their mean are generated.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=1000000, gram=True)\n >>> trlinfrac(A, method='slq', min_num_samples=20, max_num_samples=80,\n ... error_rtol=2e-4, confidence_level=0.95,\n ... outlier_significance_level=0.001, plot=True)\n\n .. image:: ../_static/images/plots/trlinfrac_slq_convergence_1.png\n :align: center\n :class: custom-dark\n\n In the left plot, the samples are shown in circles and the cumulative mean\n of the samples is shown by a solid black curve. The shaded area corresponds\n to the 95% confidence interval "":math:`\\pm 1.96 \\sigma`, which is set by\n ``confidence_level=0.95``. The samples outside the interval of 99.9% are\n considered outliers, which is set by the significance level\n ``outlier_significance_level=0.001``.\n\n In the right plot, the darker shaded area in the interval :math:`[0, 20]`\n shows the minimum number of samples and is set by ``min_num_samples=20``.\n The iterations do not stop till the minimum number of iterations is passed.\n We can observe that sampling is terminated after 55 iterations where the\n relative error of samples reaches 0.02% since we set ``error_rtol=2e-4``.\n The lighter shaded area in the interval :math:`[56, 80]` corresponds to the\n iterations that were not performed to reach the specified maximum\n iterations by ``max_num_samples=80``.\n\n **Matrix operator:**\n\n Use an object of :class:`imate.Matrix` class as an alternative method to\n pass the matrix `A` to the `trlinfrac` function.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n :emphasize-lines: 8\n\n >>> # Import matrix operator\n >>> from imate import toeplitz, trlinfrac, Matrix\n\n >>> # Generate a sample matrix (a toeplitz matrix)\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=100, gram=True)\n\n >>> # Create a matrix operator object from matrix A\n >>> Aop = Matrix(A)\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Aop\n >>> trlinfrac(Aop, method='slq')\n 141.52929878934194\n\n An advantage of passing `Aop` (instead of `A`) to the `trlinfrac` function\n will be clear when using GPU.\n\n **Computation on GPU:**\n\n The argument ``gpu=True`` performs the computations on GPU. The following\n example uses the object `Aop` created earlier.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Aop\n >>> trlinfrac(Aop, method='slq', gpu=True)\n 141.52929878934194\n\n The above function call triggers the object `Aop` to automatically load the\n ma""trix data on the GPU.\n\n One could have used `A` instead of `Aop` in the above. However, an\n advantage of using `Aop` (instead of the matrix `A` directly) is that by\n calling the above `trlinfrac` function (or another function) again on this\n matrix, the data of this matrix does not have to be re-allocated on the GPU\n device again. To highlight this point, call the above function again, but\n this time, set ``gram`` to `True` to compute something different.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Aop\n >>> trlinfrac(Aop, method='slq', gpu=True, gram=True)\n 141.52929878934194\n\n In the above example, no data is needed to be transferred from CPU host to\n GPU device again. However, if `A` was used instead of `Aop`, the data would\n have been transferred from CPU to GPU again for the second time. The `Aop`\n object holds the data on GPU for later use as long as this object does no\n go out of the scope of the python environment. Once the variable `Aop` goes\n out of scope, the matrix data on all the GPU devices will be cleaned\n automatically.\n\n **Affine matrix operator:**\n\n Use an object of :class:`imate.AffineMatrixFunction` to create the linear\n operator\n\n .. math::\n\n \\mathbf{A}(t) = \\mathbf{A} + t \\mathbf{I}.\n\n The object :math:`\\mathbf{A}(t)` can be passed to `trlinfrac` function with\n multiple values for the parameter :math:`t` to compute their\n trace-exponential all at once, as follows.\n\n .. code-block:: python\n :emphasize-lines: 8\n\n >>> # Import affine matrix function\n >>> from imate import toeplitz, trlinfrac, AffineMatrixFunction\n\n >>> # Generate a sample matrix (a toeplitz matrix)\n >>> A = toeplitz(2, 1, size=100, gram=True)\n\n >>> # Create a matrix operator object from matrix A\n >>> Aop = AffineMatrixFunction(A)\n\n >>> # A list of parameters t to pa""ss to Aop\n >>> t = [-1.0, 0.0, 1.0]\n\n >>> # Compute trace-exponential of Aop for all parameters t\n >>> trlinfrac(Aop, method='slq', parameters=t, min_num_samples=20,\n ... max_num_samples=80, error_rtol=1e-3, confidence_level=0.95,\n ... outlier_significance_level=0.001, plot=True, verbose=True)\n array([ 68.71411681, 135.88356906, 163.44156683])\n\n The output of the verbose argument is shown below. 3713 /* Profile */
3714 #if CYTHON_PROFILE
3715 static int __Pyx_TraceSetupAndCall(PyCodeObject** code,
3716  PyFrameObject** frame,
3717  PyThreadState* tstate,
3718  const char *funcname,
3719  const char *srcfile,
3720  int firstlineno) {
3721  PyObject *type, *value, *traceback;
3722  int retval;
3723  if (*frame == NULL || !CYTHON_PROFILE_REUSE_FRAME) {
3724  if (*code == NULL) {
3725  *code = __Pyx_createFrameCodeObject(funcname, srcfile, firstlineno);
3726  if (*code == NULL) return 0;
3727  }
3728  *frame = PyFrame_New(
3729  tstate, /*PyThreadState *tstate*/
3730  *code, /*PyCodeObject *code*/
3731  __pyx_d, /*PyObject *globals*/
3732  0 /*PyObject *locals*/
3733  );
3734  if (*frame == NULL) return 0;
3735  if (CYTHON_TRACE && (*frame)->f_trace == NULL) {
3736  Py_INCREF(Py_None);
3737  (*frame)->f_trace = Py_None;
3738  }
3739 #if PY_VERSION_HEX < 0x030400B1
3740  } else {
3741  (*frame)->f_tstate = tstate;
3742 #endif
3743  }
3744  __Pyx_PyFrame_SetLineNumber(*frame, firstlineno);
3745  retval = 1;
3746  __Pyx_EnterTracing(tstate);
3747  __Pyx_ErrFetchInState(tstate, &type, &value, &traceback);
3748  #if CYTHON_TRACE
3749  if (tstate->c_tracefunc)
3750  retval = tstate->c_tracefunc(tstate->c_traceobj, *frame, PyTrace_CALL, NULL) == 0;
3751  if (retval && tstate->c_profilefunc)
3752  #endif
3753  retval = tstate->c_profilefunc(tstate->c_profileobj, *frame, PyTrace_CALL, NULL) == 0;
3754  __Pyx_LeaveTracing(tstate);
3755  if (retval) {
3756  __Pyx_ErrRestoreInState(tstate, type, value, traceback);
3757  return __Pyx_IsTracing(tstate, 0, 0) && retval;
3758  } else {
3759  Py_XDECREF(type);
3760  Py_XDECREF(value);
3761  Py_XDECREF(traceback);
3762  return -1;
3763  }
3764 }
3765 static PyCodeObject *__Pyx_createFrameCodeObject(const char *funcname, const char *srcfile, int firstlineno) {
3766  PyCodeObject *py_code = 0;
3767 #if PY_MAJOR_VERSION >= 3
3768  py_code = PyCode_NewEmpty(srcfile, funcname, firstlineno);
3769  if (likely(py_code)) {
3770  py_code->co_flags |= CO_OPTIMIZED | CO_NEWLOCALS;
3771  }
3772 #else
3773  PyObject *py_srcfile = 0;
3774  PyObject *py_funcname = 0;
3775  py_funcname = PyString_FromString(funcname);
3776  if (unlikely(!py_funcname)) goto bad;
3777  py_srcfile = PyString_FromString(srcfile);
3778  if (unlikely(!py_srcfile)) goto bad;
3779  py_code = PyCode_New(
3780  0,
3781  0,
3782  0,
3783  CO_OPTIMIZED | CO_NEWLOCALS,
3784  __pyx_empty_bytes, /*PyObject *code,*/
3785  __pyx_empty_tuple, /*PyObject *consts,*/
3786  __pyx_empty_tuple, /*PyObject *names,*/
3787  __pyx_empty_tuple, /*PyObject *varnames,*/
3788  __pyx_empty_tuple, /*PyObject *freevars,*/
3789  __pyx_empty_tuple, /*PyObject *cellvars,*/
3790  py_srcfile, /*PyObject *filename,*/
3791  py_funcname, /*PyObject *name,*/
3792  firstlineno,
3793  __pyx_empty_bytes /*PyObject *lnotab*/
3794  );
3795 bad:
3796  Py_XDECREF(py_srcfile);
3797  Py_XDECREF(py_funcname);
3798 #endif
3799  return py_code;
3800 }
3801 #endif
3802 
3803 /* RaiseDoubleKeywords */
3804 static void __Pyx_RaiseDoubleKeywordsError(
3805  const char* func_name,
3806  PyObject* kw_name)
3807 {
3808  PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3809  #if PY_MAJOR_VERSION >= 3
3810  "%s() got multiple values for keyword argument '%U'", func_name, kw_name);
3811  #else
3812  "%s() got multiple values for keyword argument '%s'", func_name,
3813  PyString_AsString(kw_name));
3814  #endif
3815 }
3816 
3817 /* ParseKeywords */
3818 static int __Pyx_ParseOptionalKeywords(
3819  PyObject *kwds,
3820  PyObject **argnames[],
3821  PyObject *kwds2,
3822  PyObject *values[],
3823  Py_ssize_t num_pos_args,
3824  const char* function_name)
3825 {
3826  PyObject *key = 0, *value = 0;
3827  Py_ssize_t pos = 0;
3828  PyObject*** name;
3829  PyObject*** first_kw_arg = argnames + num_pos_args;
3830  while (PyDict_Next(kwds, &pos, &key, &value)) {
3831  name = first_kw_arg;
3832  while (*name && (**name != key)) name++;
3833  if (*name) {
3834  values[name-argnames] = value;
3835  continue;
3836  }
3837  name = first_kw_arg;
3838  #if PY_MAJOR_VERSION < 3
3839  if (likely(PyString_Check(key))) {
3840  while (*name) {
3841  if ((CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_PYPY || PyString_GET_SIZE(**name) == PyString_GET_SIZE(key))
3842  && _PyString_Eq(**name, key)) {
3843  values[name-argnames] = value;
3844  break;
3845  }
3846  name++;
3847  }
3848  if (*name) continue;
3849  else {
3850  PyObject*** argname = argnames;
3851  while (argname != first_kw_arg) {
3852  if ((**argname == key) || (
3853  (CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_PYPY || PyString_GET_SIZE(**argname) == PyString_GET_SIZE(key))
3854  && _PyString_Eq(**argname, key))) {
3855  goto arg_passed_twice;
3856  }
3857  argname++;
3858  }
3859  }
3860  } else
3861  #endif
3862  if (likely(PyUnicode_Check(key))) {
3863  while (*name) {
3864  int cmp = (**name == key) ? 0 :
3865  #if !CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_PYPY && PY_MAJOR_VERSION >= 3
3866  (__Pyx_PyUnicode_GET_LENGTH(**name) != __Pyx_PyUnicode_GET_LENGTH(key)) ? 1 :
3867  #endif
3868  PyUnicode_Compare(**name, key);
3869  if (cmp < 0 && unlikely(PyErr_Occurred())) goto bad;
3870  if (cmp == 0) {
3871  values[name-argnames] = value;
3872  break;
3873  }
3874  name++;
3875  }
3876  if (*name) continue;
3877  else {
3878  PyObject*** argname = argnames;
3879  while (argname != first_kw_arg) {
3880  int cmp = (**argname == key) ? 0 :
3881  #if !CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_PYPY && PY_MAJOR_VERSION >= 3
3882  (__Pyx_PyUnicode_GET_LENGTH(**argname) != __Pyx_PyUnicode_GET_LENGTH(key)) ? 1 :
3883  #endif
3884  PyUnicode_Compare(**argname, key);
3885  if (cmp < 0 && unlikely(PyErr_Occurred())) goto bad;
3886  if (cmp == 0) goto arg_passed_twice;
3887  argname++;
3888  }
3889  }
3890  } else
3891  goto invalid_keyword_type;
3892  if (kwds2) {
3893  if (unlikely(PyDict_SetItem(kwds2, key, value))) goto bad;
3894  } else {
3895  goto invalid_keyword;
3896  }
3897  }
3898  return 0;
3899 arg_passed_twice:
3900  __Pyx_RaiseDoubleKeywordsError(function_name, key);
3901  goto bad;
3902 invalid_keyword_type:
3903  PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3904  "%.200s() keywords must be strings", function_name);
3905  goto bad;
3906 invalid_keyword:
3907  PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3908  #if PY_MAJOR_VERSION < 3
3909  "%.200s() got an unexpected keyword argument '%.200s'",
3910  function_name, PyString_AsString(key));
3911  #else
3912  "%s() got an unexpected keyword argument '%U'",
3913  function_name, key);
3914  #endif
3915 bad:
3916  return -1;
3917 }
3918 
3919 /* RaiseArgTupleInvalid */
3920 static void __Pyx_RaiseArgtupleInvalid(
3921  const char* func_name,
3922  int exact,
3923  Py_ssize_t num_min,
3924  Py_ssize_t num_max,
3925  Py_ssize_t num_found)
3926 {
3927  Py_ssize_t num_expected;
3928  const char *more_or_less;
3929  if (num_found < num_min) {
3930  num_expected = num_min;
3931  more_or_less = "at least";
3932  } else {
3933  num_expected = num_max;
3934  more_or_less = "at most";
3935  }
3936  if (exact) {
3937  more_or_less = "exactly";
3938  }
3939  PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3940  "%.200s() takes %.8s %" CYTHON_FORMAT_SSIZE_T "d positional argument%.1s (%" CYTHON_FORMAT_SSIZE_T "d given)",
3941  func_name, more_or_less, num_expected,
3942  (num_expected == 1) ? "" : "s", num_found);
3943 }

3945 /* PyDictVersioning */
3946 #if CYTHON_USE_DICT_VERSIONS && CYTHON_USE_TYPE_SLOTS
3947 static CYTHON_INLINE PY_UINT64_T __Pyx_get_tp_dict_version(PyObject *obj) {
3948  PyObject *dict = Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_dict;
3949  return likely(dict) ? __PYX_GET_DICT_VERSION(dict) : 0;
3950 }
3951 static CYTHON_INLINE PY_UINT64_T __Pyx_get_object_dict_version(PyObject *obj) {
3952  PyObject **dictptr = NULL;
3953  Py_ssize_t offset = Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_dictoffset;
3954  if (offset) {
3955 #if CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_CPYTHON
3956  dictptr = (likely(offset > 0)) ? (PyObject **) ((char *)obj + offset) : _PyObject_GetDictPtr(obj);
3957 #else
3958  dictptr = _PyObject_GetDictPtr(obj);
3959 #endif
3960  }
3961  return (dictptr && *dictptr) ? __PYX_GET_DICT_VERSION(*dictptr) : 0;
3962 }
3963 static CYTHON_INLINE int __Pyx_object_dict_version_matches(PyObject* obj, PY_UINT64_T tp_dict_version, PY_UINT64_T obj_dict_version) {
3964  PyObject *dict = Py_TYPE(obj)->tp_dict;
3965  if (unlikely(!dict) || unlikely(tp_dict_version != __PYX_GET_DICT_VERSION(dict)))
3966  return 0;
3967  return obj_dict_version == __Pyx_get_object_dict_version(obj);
3968 }
3969 #endif

3972 #if CYTHON_USE_DICT_VERSIONS
3973 static PyObject *__Pyx__GetModuleGlobalName(PyObject *name, PY_UINT64_T *dict_version, PyObject **dict_cached_value)
3974 #else
3975 static CYTHON_INLINE PyObject *__Pyx__GetModuleGlobalName(PyObject *name)
3976 #endif
3977 {
3978  PyObject *result;
3979 #if !CYTHON_AVOID_BORROWED_REFS
3980 #if CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_CPYTHON && PY_VERSION_HEX >= 0x030500A1

3982  __PYX_UPDATE_DICT_CACHE(__pyx_d, result, *dict_cached_value, *dict_version)
3983  if (likely(result)) {
3984  return __Pyx_NewRef(result);
3985  } else if (unlikely(PyErr_Occurred())) {
3986  return NULL;

3988 #else

3990  __PYX_UPDATE_DICT_CACHE(__pyx_d, result, *dict_cached_value, *dict_version)
3991  if (likely(result)) {

3994 #endif
3995 #else

3997  __PYX_UPDATE_DICT_CACHE(__pyx_d, result, *dict_cached_value, *dict_version)
3998  if (likely(result)) {
3999  return __Pyx_NewRef(result);
4000  }
4001  PyErr_Clear();
4002 #endif
